== Raijin Shrine ==

{{shrine
|name = Raijin Shrine
|image = [[File:雷神社（旭市）.jpg|250px|Raijin Shrine (Asahi City) Worship Hall]]<br />Worship Hall<br />{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=11|frame-align=center|frame-width=250|coord={{coord|35|44|27.3|N|140|41|48.9|E}}}}
|location = {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|12=draft}}, {{ill|Asahi, Chiba|ja|旭市|12=draft}} Mihiro 1371
|coordinates = {{coord|35|44|27.3|N|140|41|48.9|E|region:JP-12_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}
|enshrined deity = {{ill|Ame-no-hohi|ja|天穂日命|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kamo-wake-ikazuchi no Mikoto|ja|賀茂別雷命|12=draft}}
|status = Former {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft}}
|established = 53rd year of {{ill|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇|12=draft}}
|main hall = Nagare-zukuri
|annual festival = June 15
}}

'''Raijin Shrine''' (雷神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in Mihiro, {{ill|Asahi, Chiba|ja|旭市|12=draft}}, in the former {{ill|Shimōsa Province|ja|下総国|12=draft}}, Kaijō District. Its former shrine rank was {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft}}.

The primary enshrined deity is {{ill|Ame-no-hohi|ja|天穂日命|12=draft}}, with {{ill|Kamo-wake-ikazuchi no Mikoto|ja|賀茂別雷命|12=draft}} also worshipped.

== Overview ==

According to legend, the shrine was founded when {{ill|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇|12=draft}}, mourning the death of his son {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武尊|1=Yamato Takeru|lt=Prince Yamato Takeru|3=ヤマトタケル|12=draft}} in Nobono, {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|12=draft}}, constructed a shrine at the eastern edge of {{ill|Tsubaki Sea|ja|椿海|12=draft}} to protect the eastern sea. Later, {{ill|Kutsuki no Atae|ja|久都伎直|12=draft}}, appointed as the ruler of Lower Kaijō Province, enshrined his ancestral deity, Ame-no-hohi. In 793 (Enryaku 12), the deity "Wakeraijin" was invited from {{ill|Kamo Wakeikazuchi Shrine|ja|賀茂別雷神社|12=draft}} and enshrined alongside, with Emperor {{ill|Kanmu|ja|桓武天皇|12=draft}} granting the title "Raijin-ōkami."

The current shrine building was completed in 1910 (Meiji 43). Subsidiary shrines include:
* {{ill|Tsushima Ōkami|ja|津島大神|12=draft}} (founded 1804, Kyōwa 4)
* Various {{ill|Tanokami|ja|田の神|12=draft}} deities (1828, Bunsei 11)
* {{ill|Tennōgū|ja|天王宮|12=draft}} (1855, Ansei 2)
* {{ill|Sekison Daigongen|ja|石尊大権現|12=draft}} (1775, An'ei 4)
* {{ill|Konpira Shrine|ja|金毘羅神|12=draft}} (1805, Bunka 2)
* {{ill|Hōsōgami|ja|疱瘡神|12=draft}} (1844, Tenpō 15)
* {{ill|Tenmangū|ja|天満宮|12=draft}} (1977, Shōwa 52)
* {{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社|12=draft}} (relocated in 2007, Heisei 19)

== Festivals and Events ==

Together with {{ill|Tōdaisha|ja|東大社|12=draft}} and {{ill|Toyotama-hime Shrine (Katori)|ja|豊玉姫神社|12=draft}}, Raijin Shrine hosts a {{ill|shikinen shinkōsai|ja|式年神幸祭|12=draft}} every 20 years. The "Kurahashi no Miroku Sambasō" dance, performed as a forerunner to the portable shrine procession, is considered a form of {{ill|Kashima Odori|ja|鹿島踊り|12=draft}}. Its unique formation of dancers moving in a line has led to its designation as an {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Property of Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#無形民俗文化財|12=draft}}.

== Access ==

* 15-minute walk from {{ill|Kurahashi Station|ja|倉橋駅|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Sōbu Main Line|ja|総武本線|12=draft}}, operated by {{ill|JR East|ja|東日本旅客鉄道|12=draft}}.

== References ==

* "Zenkoku Jinja Meikan, Volume 1," Zenkoku Jinja Meikan Kankōkai Shigaku Center, 1977 (Shōwa 52).
* "Chiba-ken no Chimei" (Japanese Historical Place Names Series 12), Heibonsha, 1996. ISBN 978-4-582-49012-1

== External Links ==

* [http://raijinjya.jp/ Official Website of Raijin Shrine]
